# deploy/caddy/Caddyfile
#
# Reverse-proxy in front of the waterwall admin server (127.0.0.1:8889).
# The waterwall admin stays loopback-only and untouched. Caddy is the
# public face for whichever access path the operator runs.
#
# Public URL: https://waterwall.example.com/waterwall/
# Path:       /waterwall/*  (page + JSON; the rest of the URL namespace
#                            is free for other apps on the same host)
#
# The waterwall admin is built with `mount_prefix="/waterwall"` only
# when the operator exports WATERWALL_MOUNT_PREFIX=/waterwall before
# starting mitmdump. With the env var unset, the admin serves the
# API at /admin/state (legacy root-mount) and these Caddyfile rules
# will forward to a 404. Either:
#   (a) export WATERWALL_MOUNT_PREFIX=/waterwall in the unit/env that
#       starts mitmdump, OR
#   (b) change the @waterwall matchers below to plain "/" if you
#       want the page exposed at the URL root instead.
#
# Three access paths, all converging on this Caddyfile:
#
#   1. Tailscale      tailscaled terminates TLS, forwards to the
#                     loopback Caddy listener (http://127.0.0.1:8443).
#                     See tailscale.md for the one-liner.
#
#   2. Cloudflare     cloudflared connects out to Cloudflare's edge,
#                     Cloudflare Access policy on /waterwall* gates
#                     the public path, the local hop lands on the
#                     loopback Caddy listener. See cloudflared.yml.example.
#
#   3. Wireguard      Caddy listens directly on the wg interface IP at
#                     :443, serves HTTPS for waterwall.example.com to peers.
#                     Caddy's internal CA signs the cert; export and
#                     install the CA on peer devices.
#
# The waterwall admin's loopback binding is unchanged. None of these
# configs widen it — the reverse proxy is the only thing exposed.
#
# Everything that is NOT /waterwall/* gets a 404 from Caddy. The
# wg listener and the loopback listener each enforce this. The page
# and JSON live at the prefixed path; the rest of waterwall.example.com
# is a no-op surface.

# -------------------------------------------------------------- 1. loopback
# HTTP only — used by cloudflared tunnel and `tailscale serve`. Caddy
# terminates the local connection and proxies to the admin on
# loopback. TLS is handled at the upstream tunnel; the local hop is
# plain HTTP because both ends are loopback.
http://127.0.0.1:8443 {
	@waterwall path /waterwall /waterwall/*
	handle @waterwall {
		reverse_proxy 127.0.0.1:8889
	}

	# --- mitmweb (optional) -----------------------------------------
	# Same block as on the wg listener below; duplicated here so the
	# Tailscale / Cloudflare paths can reach mitmweb too. See APPS.md.
	# @mitmweb path /mitmweb /mitmweb/*
	# handle @mitmweb {
	# 	uri strip_prefix /mitmweb
	# 	reverse_proxy 127.0.0.1:8081
	# }

	# Anything else on the loopback listener is 404 — the admin's
	# other endpoints (healthz, root, etc.) are not exposed here.
	respond "not found" 404
}

# ----------------------------------------------------- 2. wireguard
# HTTPS on the wg interface IP. Caddy terminates TLS for
# waterwall.example.com and proxies /waterwall/* to the admin. Other paths
# get 404 so the wg listener can't be used to probe the rest of the
# host's URL namespace.
#
# TLS: Caddy's internal CA. Caddy generates a self-signed cert and
# the CA at first start. The operator exports the CA cert from
# /var/lib/caddy/pki/authorities/local/root.crt and installs it on
# peer devices (or accepts the browser warning once per device). For
# a public cert instead, replace `tls internal` with `tls <email>`
# (Let's Encrypt via ACME DNS-01, since waterwall.example.com needs DNS
# validation) or supply your own cert + key paths.
https://waterwall.example.com {
	bind 10.0.0.1 # <-- set to your wg interface IP, e.g. 10.0.0.1

	tls internal

	@waterwall path /waterwall /waterwall/*
	handle @waterwall {
		reverse_proxy 127.0.0.1:8889
	}

	# --- mitmweb (optional) -----------------------------------------
	# Uncomment to also expose the mitmproxy web UI at
	# https://waterwall.example.com/mitmweb/. The mitmweb JS uses relative
	# URLs internally so `uri strip_prefix` works cleanly. See
	# APPS.md for the full feasibility analysis and gotchas (auth,
	# CSRF, WebSocket).
	# @mitmweb path /mitmweb /mitmweb/*
	# handle @mitmweb {
	# 	uri strip_prefix /mitmweb
	# 	reverse_proxy 127.0.0.1:8081
	# }

	respond "not found" 404
}

# -------------------------------------------------- 3. tailscale (docs)
# Tailscale is configured out of band via `tailscale serve`, not here.
# See deploy/caddy/tailscale.md for the one-liner that points
# https://<host>.<tailnet>.ts.net/waterwall/ at http://127.0.0.1:8443/waterwall/.
# Caddy's loopback listener proxies the path through unchanged; the
# admin's mount_prefix matches the public path.
